p: The 13C spectrum showed a signal at δ C 203.9 for carbonyl carbon and four methyl carbons at δ C 21.7 (C-12 or C-13), δ C 22.6 (C-12 or C-13), δ C 26.7 (C-14), and δ C 22.2 (C-15) as well as four methynic carbons at δ C 131.7 (C-1), δ C 123 (C-2), δ C 118 (C-3), and δ C 46.1 (C-5). The chemical shifts δ C 123.0 (C-2), δ C 118.0 (C-3), δ C 22.6 (C-12 or C-13), and δ C 22.2 (C-15) are significantly different when compared to those reported in the literature for the synthetic compound 1 [ 19], δ C 118 (C-2), δ C 123 (C-3), δ C 22.2 (C-12 or C-13), and δ C 22.6 (C-15) [ 19]. With COSY, it was possible to correlate the couplings between the signals at δ H 5.33 (d, J = 9.4 Hz, H-3) with δ H 5.76 (d, J = 9.4, 5.3 Hz, H-2) and δ H 2.66 (dd, J = 10.6, 4.8 Hz, H-6) with δ H 2.24 (m, H-6’) and δ H 2.00 (dd, J = 10.6, 4.8 Hz, H-5). The HMBC spectrum analysis showed a correlation of C-7 ( δ C 132.6) with H-6 ( δ H 2.66), H-6’ ( δ H 2.24), H-12 or H-13 ( δ H 1.79), and H-12 or H-13 ( δ H 1.94). The correlation of C-3 ( δ C 118.0) with H-15 ( δ H 1.85) and C-9 ( δ C 53.4) with H-14 ( δ H 1.04) confirmed the positions of the H-14 and H-15 methyl groups. The position of the carbonyl group C-8 ( δ C 203.9) correlated with the diastereotopic hydrogens H-6 ( δ H 2.66) and H-6’ ( δ H 2.24) as well as H-9 ( δ H 2.47) and H-9’ ( δ H 2.30).
